&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;sin i &amp;divide; sin r = constant&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Snell&amp;#39;s law states that the ratio of the sine of the angle of incidence (i) to the sine of the angle of refraction (r) is constant for a given pair of media and is equal to the refractive index.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The mathematical expression for Snell&amp;#39;s law is &lt;strong&gt;sin i &amp;divide; sin r = n&lt;/strong&gt;, where &lt;strong&gt;n&lt;/strong&gt; is the refractive index of the second medium with respect to the first.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This law explains the bending of light when it passes from one medium to another with a different refractive index.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Snell&amp;#39;s law is crucial in understanding optical phenomena such as refraction and total internal reflection.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The constant value (n) depends on the optical density of the two media involved in the transition of light.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Refractive Index (n):&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The refractive index is a dimensionless quantity that describes how light propagates through a medium.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is defined as the ratio of the speed of light in a vacuum to the speed of light in the medium: &lt;strong&gt;n = c/v&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Angle of Incidence (i):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is the angle between the incident ray and the normal (perpendicular) to the surface at the point of incidence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Angle of Refraction (r):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is the angle between the refracted ray and the normal to the surface at the point of refraction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Total Internal Reflection:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This phenomenon occurs when the angle of incidence exceeds the critical angle, causing the light to reflect entirely within the denser medium.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Snell&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in designing lenses, prisms, and optical instruments like microscopes and telescopes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Essential in fiber optic communication for guiding light signals through cables.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;They are multicellular and may be secretory&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;ul color:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Trichomes&lt;/strong&gt; are epidermal outgrowths that can be present on the stem, leaves, and even other parts of the plant.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are typically &lt;strong&gt;multicellular&lt;/strong&gt;, consisting of several cells, and may take on various forms such as scales, hairs, or glandular structures.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Trichomes can have &lt;strong&gt;secretory functions&lt;/strong&gt;, producing substances like essential oils, resins, or other chemicals that help deter herbivores or attract pollinators.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They also play a role in &lt;strong&gt;water retention&lt;/strong&gt; by reducing water loss from the plant surface, helping plants survive in dry environments.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Trichomes may protect plants from &lt;strong&gt;excessive sunlight&lt;/strong&gt; by reflecting light and reducing heat absorption.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In some plants, trichomes act as a defense mechanism by being sharp or sticky, preventing pests and herbivores from damaging the plant.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are highly diverse in structure and function, depending on the species and environmental conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Intercalary&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Intercalary meristem is a type of meristematic tissue located at the nodes of plants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is responsible for the regrowth of grasses and contributes to the elongation of internodes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Intercalary meristems allow rapid regeneration in grasses after grazing or mowing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This tissue is present in monocots, particularly in grasses, which aids their survival in environments with regular disturbances.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike apical meristem, which is found at the tips of roots and shoots, intercalary meristem is strategically located at the base of nodes and leaf blades.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Meristematic Tissue:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Meristematic tissues are responsible for the growth of plants and consist of actively dividing cells.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These tissues are classified into apical, lateral, and intercalary based on their location.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Apical meristem contributes to the primary growth at the tips of roots and shoots.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Lateral meristem is involved in secondary growth, leading to an increase in the girth of the plant.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Monocots vs. Dicots:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Monocots, like grasses, have intercalary meristems that help them regrow quickly after damage.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Dicots generally lack intercalary meristems and rely on apical and lateral meristems for growth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Node and Internode:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Nodes are points on the stem where leaves or branches originate.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Internodes are the regions between two nodes, which elongate due to intercalary meristem activity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Adaptation in Grasses:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Grasses are adapted to survive grazing, fire, or mowing due to the presence of intercalary meristems.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These tissues regenerate leaf blades and stems quickly, ensuring survival and growth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Dienes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A molecule called diene &lt;/strong&gt;has&lt;strong&gt; two double bonds between its carbon&lt;/strong&gt; atoms and is &lt;strong&gt;unsaturated.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Diene&lt;/strong&gt; is employed in industry as a&lt;strong&gt; complex polymer&amp;#39;s monomer constituent.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is also used in &lt;strong&gt;Organic Synthesis.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Dienes are divided into&lt;strong&gt; three groups&lt;/strong&gt; based on where the&lt;strong&gt; double bond is located &lt;/strong&gt;relative to the rest of the molecule:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;cumulated diene&lt;/strong&gt; is one that has &lt;strong&gt;two consecutive double bonds&lt;/strong&gt; on nearby Carbon atoms. They go by the name&lt;strong&gt; Allene too.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;conjugated diene&lt;/strong&gt; is a compound with &lt;strong&gt;two conjugated double bonds&lt;/strong&gt; that are spaced apart by just&lt;strong&gt; one bond.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Two double bonds&lt;/strong&gt; that are spaced apart by&lt;strong&gt; two or more double bond&lt;/strong&gt;s make up an&lt;strong&gt; isolated diene.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Terpenes:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Terpenes are a group of &lt;strong&gt;organic compounds&lt;/strong&gt; with the formula&lt;strong&gt; (C&lt;sub&gt;5&lt;/sub&gt;H&lt;sub&gt;8&lt;/sub&gt;)n,&lt;/strong&gt; where &lt;strong&gt;n is greater than 1.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Alkyne:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Alkynes are hydrocarbons that have &lt;strong&gt;triple bonds between carbon atoms.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When it comes to&lt;strong&gt; molecules with one triple bond&lt;/strong&gt;, their usual formula is &lt;strong&gt;C&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;H&lt;sub&gt;2n-2&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sub&gt;(and no rings).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Transverse wave&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Transverse waves&lt;/strong&gt; are the type of waves that are formed on a &lt;strong&gt;stretched string&lt;/strong&gt; when it is plucked or disturbed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In a transverse wave, the &lt;strong&gt;particles of the medium&lt;/strong&gt; move in a direction that is &lt;strong&gt;perpendicular&lt;/strong&gt; to the direction of wave propagation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a string is plucked, the &lt;strong&gt;up-and-down motion&lt;/strong&gt; of the string creates a wave pattern where the crests and troughs are visible.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The wave travels along the length of the string, but the &lt;strong&gt;displacement&lt;/strong&gt; of the string particles is at right angles to this direction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This type of wave is characterized by &lt;strong&gt;wavelength, frequency, amplitude,&lt;/strong&gt; and speed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples of transverse waves include &lt;strong&gt;light waves, water waves&lt;/strong&gt;, and waves on a string.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Such waves do not require a medium for propagation (if electromagnetic), but on a string, they propagate through the medium of the string material.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Torsional wave&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Torsional waves&lt;/strong&gt; involve the twisting motion of particles around the axis of wave propagation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Such waves are commonly found in &lt;strong&gt;solid bars&lt;/strong&gt; and structures like &lt;strong&gt;shafts&lt;/strong&gt; in mechanical systems.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are not typically formed on a stretched string.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electromagnetic wave&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electromagnetic waves&lt;/strong&gt; are waves that do not require a medium for propagation and consist of oscillating &lt;strong&gt;electric and magnetic fields.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include &lt;strong&gt;light, radio waves, and X-rays.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These waves are not formed on a stretched string as they are inherently different in nature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Surface wave&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Surface waves&lt;/strong&gt; occur at the boundary between two different mediums, such as air and water.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include &lt;strong&gt;water waves&lt;/strong&gt;, where the motion of particles is a combination of longitudinal and transverse motion.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These waves are not relevant to the case of a stretched string.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Human Excretory system:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The system of the organ which is used to remove the waste product out from the body is called&lt;strong&gt; the human excretory system&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The major waste product generated in the human body is urea, along with which some other toxins are also generated.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Urea is eliminated by kidneys by the process of urination and solid wastes are removed from the body by the intestines.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Excretory system organs:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/09/F1_Prabhat_Madhu_02.09.20_D6.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 249px; height: 331px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kidneys:&lt;/strong&gt;It is a bean shaped organ. Its function is to clean blood and eliminate the waste from the blood in form of urine&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is present in the abdomen, just below the diaphragm, and is protected by ribs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Each kidney weighs 120g to 170 g and 10-12 cm long and 5-7 cm wide and is the size of a fist.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kidneys are made up of subunits called Nephron&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;2.&lt;strong&gt;Ureters: &lt;/strong&gt;​Each kidney is connected to the rinal pelvis by a thin muscular tube, this tube is called as &lt;strong&gt;Ureter.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its function is to propel urine from the kidney to the urinary Bladder from time to time.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; 3&lt;strong&gt;.Bladders:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;It&amp;#39;s the organ that controls the passage of urine, it is a muscular sac-like structure.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The average capacity of the bladder is &lt;strong&gt;400-600 ml.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It holds urine until its capacity expels, or till it gets full.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; 4.&lt;strong&gt;Urethra: &lt;/strong&gt;The Urethra is a tube made up of fibro muscular tissue that arises from the lower opening of the bladder, and open to the external uretral orifice.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It helps to expel urine through the&amp;nbsp;body, in the male it is also the tube that consist of the sperms.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In kidneys, the Nephron is the functional unit, each kidney has as many as 1 million nephrons in each human kidney.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The basic functions of the &lt;strong&gt;nephron&lt;/strong&gt; are to carry &lt;strong&gt;out secretion&lt;/strong&gt; as well as the &lt;strong&gt;process of excretion &lt;/strong&gt;and also called as&lt;strong&gt; filtration unit of the human excretory system&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Each nephron is made up of a&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Malpighian body.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Nephrons&lt;/strong&gt; are of two types which are &lt;strong&gt;Cortical Nephrons&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Juxtamedullary Nephrons&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;So, the Nephron is the part that is also called as filtration unit of the Excretory unit.&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Phlogiston theory&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Phlogiston theory&lt;/strong&gt; was a scientific theory proposed in the late 17th century to explain processes of &lt;strong&gt;combustion and rusting&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It suggested that a substance called &lt;strong&gt;phlogiston&lt;/strong&gt; was released when materials burned or oxidized.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to the theory, substances rich in phlogiston burned more easily, while substances that had lost phlogiston were considered &amp;quot;dephlogisticated.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The theory was eventually replaced by the &lt;strong&gt;caloric theory&lt;/strong&gt; and later by modern theories based on the &lt;strong&gt;laws of thermodynamics&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;atomic structure.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The work of scientists such as &lt;strong&gt;Antoine Lavoisier&lt;/strong&gt; demonstrated that combustion involved the chemical combination of substances with &lt;strong&gt;oxygen&lt;/strong&gt;, debunking the phlogiston theory.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kinetic theory&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Kinetic theory&lt;/strong&gt; of heat explains that heat is a form of energy associated with the &lt;strong&gt;random motion of particles&lt;/strong&gt; (atoms or molecules) within a substance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a modern theory and is based on &lt;strong&gt;statistical mechanics&lt;/strong&gt;, not related to the caloric or phlogiston theories.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thermodynamic theory&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Thermodynamic theory&lt;/strong&gt; deals with the principles of energy conservation, heat transfer, and the relationships among temperature, pressure, and volume.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a &lt;strong&gt;macroscopic theory&lt;/strong&gt; that replaced earlier theories like the caloric theory.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Entropy theory&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Entropy theory&lt;/strong&gt; is part of thermodynamics, describing the degree of &lt;strong&gt;disorder or randomness&lt;/strong&gt; in a system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It has no direct connection with the outdated concepts of caloric or phlogiston theories.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;reactants&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reactants&lt;/strong&gt; are the substances that are present at the beginning of a &lt;strong&gt;chemical reaction&lt;/strong&gt;. These are the starting materials that undergo a chemical change.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;In a chemical equation, reactants are usually written on the &lt;strong&gt;left-hand side&lt;/strong&gt; of the arrow (&amp;rarr;), indicating their transformation during the reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;Reactants undergo chemical changes to form &lt;strong&gt;products&lt;/strong&gt;, which are the substances that are produced as a result of the reaction. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, the statement is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1041&quot; data-start=&quot;850&quot;&gt;For example, in the reaction &lt;strong&gt;2H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; + O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;rarr; 2H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O&lt;/strong&gt;, the reactants are hydrogen (H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;) and oxygen (O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;), and the product is water (H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1162&quot; data-start=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;Reactants are crucial in understanding the nature of a chemical reaction and predicting the products formed. &lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is reactants.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reactants:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2410&quot; data-start=&quot;2195&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reactants&lt;/strong&gt; are the initial substances in a chemical reaction that undergo transformation to produce new substances, called &lt;strong&gt;products&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2684&quot; data-start=&quot;2415&quot;&gt;They are used to determine the stoichiometric relationships in a reaction, which helps in calculating the amount of products formed.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3071&quot; data-start=&quot;2865&quot;&gt;Reactants may exist in any state of matter: &lt;strong&gt;solid, liquid, gas, or aqueous&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Components of a Chemical Reaction:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3250&quot; data-start=&quot;3076&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Products:&lt;/strong&gt; These are the substances formed as a result of the reaction. They are written on the right-hand side of the chemical equation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3402&quot; data-start=&quot;3301&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Intermediates:&lt;/strong&gt; These are temporary substances formed in the middle steps of a reaction, which further react to form the final products.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3580&quot; data-start=&quot;3407&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Catalysts:&lt;/strong&gt; These are substances that increase the rate of a chemical reaction without being consumed in the process. They lower the activation energy required for the reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Characteristics of Reactants:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4636&quot; data-start=&quot;4411&quot;&gt;Reactants are consumed during the chemical reaction and are not present in the final products.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4761&quot; data-start=&quot;4641&quot;&gt;The nature and amount of reactants directly affect the rate of the reaction and the quantity of products formed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples of Reactants:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5043&quot; data-start=&quot;4817&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Combustion reaction:&lt;/strong&gt; In the reaction CH&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt; + 2O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;rarr; CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; + 2H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O, the reactants are methane (CH&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;) and oxygen (O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5259&quot; data-start=&quot;5048&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Photosynthesis:&lt;/strong&gt; The reactants are carbon dioxide (CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;) and water (H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O), which, in the presence of sunlight, form glucose (C&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt;H&lt;sub&gt;12&lt;/sub&gt;O&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt;) and oxygen (O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the female reproductive system, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;female produces eggs&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;whereas the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;male having sperms&lt;/span&gt;. When they fuse forms a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;zygote&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Which after fertilization&amp;nbsp;converts into an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;embryo.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Gamete:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;The gamete&amp;nbsp;is also termed reproductive/sex cells. The female gamete is called ova/egg cells whereas the male gamete is sperm.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Embryo:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;It is the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;early-stage development of the unborn baby&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the multicellular organism.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Egg:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;It is a female reproductive cell or ovaries, this is the part of the gamete.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Ovum:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Female reproductive cells ovum (singular) or&amp;nbsp;ovaries (plural). When this fuse to sperms form a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;zygote.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/08/F1_Aman_Madhu_05.08.20_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 212px; width: 410px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Out of these four gametes (Ovum/egg + sperm), Egg and Ovum are the same in meaning whereas the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Embryo is the later developed process.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The process of fusion of the male and the female gametes is called&amp;nbsp;fertilisation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frequency&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Frequency refers to the number of compressions or rarefactions passing a given point per unit time in a sound wave.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is typically measured in &lt;strong&gt;Hertz (Hz)&lt;/strong&gt;, which represents cycles per second.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;High-frequency sound waves correspond to a high pitch, while low-frequency sound waves correspond to a low pitch.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The frequency of a sound wave determines its tone, distinguishing one sound from another.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In physics, frequency is an essential parameter in the study of wave phenomena, including sound and electromagnetic waves.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Amplitude&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Amplitude measures the maximum displacement of particles in a sound wave from their equilibrium position.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is related to the loudness of the sound&amp;mdash;the greater the amplitude, the louder the sound.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wavelength&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Wavelength is the distance between two consecutive compressions or rarefactions in a sound wave.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is inversely proportional to frequency: higher frequency means shorter wavelength.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Loudness&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Loudness is a subjective measure of sound intensity perceived by the human ear.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is influenced by both the amplitude of the sound wave and the sensitivity of the listener&amp;#39;s ear.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sound Wave Basics&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sound waves are longitudinal waves that propagate through a medium by compressing and rarefying particles.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The speed of sound depends on the medium&amp;#39;s properties, such as density and elasticity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
